# TDD — Core Philosophy

## 1. Core Principle

All production code MUST originate from a failing test.

❌ Writing production code without a failing test is FORBIDDEN  

---

## 2. TDD Cycle (STRICT INVARIANT)

### RED
- Write EXACTLY ONE failing test
- Test must follow Given / When / Then
- Test must represent ONE behavior
- No production code allowed

---

### GREEN
- Implement the MINIMUM code required to pass the test

❌ Do NOT:
- Add extra features
- Anticipate future requirements
- Introduce new fields or parameters without test requirement

---

### REFACTOR
- Improve structure WITHOUT changing behavior

Constraints:
- Tests MUST NOT be modified
- All tests MUST remain passing

---

## 3. Cycle Constraints

- One cycle = one behavior
- One behavior = one test
- No skipping phases
- No combining phases

---

## 4. Behavior Rule

A valid test MUST:
- Describe observable behavior
- Avoid implementation details
- Remain valid after refactoring

---

## 5. Anti-Overengineering Rule

❌ Adding behavior, fields, or logic not required by the failing test is FORBIDDEN  
(e.g., adding `customerId` without test requirement)

---

## 6. Refactor Safety Rule

Refactoring is valid ONLY if:
- Behavior remains unchanged
- Tests remain unchanged
- All tests pass